00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.400
PROFESSOR: So far in our
discussion of probability,

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:29.210
we've focused our attention
on the probability

00:00:29.210 --> 00:00:33.220
that some kind of event
occurs-- the probability you

00:00:33.220 --> 00:00:36.600
win the Monty Hall game,
the probability that you get

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:40.870
a heads when you flip a
coin, the probability we all

00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:44.570
have different birthdays in
the room-- that kind of thing.

00:00:44.570 --> 00:00:47.760
In each case, the event
happens or it doesn't.

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:50.630
It's a zero-one kind of thing.

00:00:50.630 --> 00:00:52.710
For the rest of
the course, we're

00:00:52.710 --> 00:00:56.460
going to start talking about
more complicated situations.

00:00:56.460 --> 00:00:58.840
Instead of talking
about zero-one events,

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:00.890
like winning or
losing, we're going

00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:04.610
to start talking about
how much you win.

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:06.926
Instead of talking
about whether or not

00:01:06.926 --> 00:01:08.970
you get a heads in
a coin flip, we're

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:10.930
going to talk about
flipping lots of coins

00:01:10.930 --> 00:01:16.080
and asking how many
heads did you get?

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:21.420
Now, this involves the
notion of a random variable

00:01:21.420 --> 00:01:24.990
to count how much or how
many in a random situation.

00:01:24.990 --> 00:01:27.250
And actually, the
name is sort of weird.

00:01:27.250 --> 00:01:29.650
It's not a variable at all.

00:01:29.650 --> 00:01:33.080
In fact, a random variable
is a function from the sample

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:34.190
space to the real numbers.

00:01:45.390 --> 00:01:56.220
See random variable R is a
function R from the sample

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:00.512
space to the reals.

00:02:00.512 --> 00:02:02.470
So this is the random
variable, and we'll often

00:02:02.470 --> 00:02:05.040
denote that by rv.

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:07.980
This is the sample space
of all possible outcomes.

00:02:11.190 --> 00:02:12.460
And this is just the reals.

00:02:17.460 --> 00:02:19.600
All right, so in other
words, a random variable

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:22.150
is just a way of
assigning a real number

00:02:22.150 --> 00:02:25.440
to each possible outcome.

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:28.085
For example, say that
we toss three coins.

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:45.080
We could let R equal the number
of heads among the three coins.

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:47.040
And R is thus a random variable.

00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:51.920
For example, for the outcome
where the first coin is heads,

00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:54.050
the second is tails,
and the third is heads,

00:02:54.050 --> 00:02:57.610
R would be the real
number 2, indicating I

00:02:57.610 --> 00:02:59.310
got two heads in that outcome.

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:07.300
We could also define another
value called M, which we'll say

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:16.680
is 1 if all three coins match,
if they're all the same,

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:19.987
and 0 otherwise, if
they're not all the same.

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:32.780
For example, M on the outcome
heads, heads, tails is 0.

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:36.190
M on the outcome
tails, tails, tails

00:03:36.190 --> 00:03:38.120
would be 1, because
they all are the same.

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:42.120
Is M a random variable?

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:49.370
Yeah, it assigns a value, a
real number, to every outcome.

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:52.110
And that value is
either 0 or 1, depending

00:03:52.110 --> 00:03:53.980
on if all the coins match.

00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:56.870
In fact, it's a very special
kind of random variable

00:03:56.870 --> 00:03:59.520
that's called an indicator
random variable, also

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:03.820
known as Bernoulli or
characteristic random variable,

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:05.270
because it's zero-one.

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:21.209
An indicator also
known as a Bernoulli

00:04:21.209 --> 00:04:35.890
or characteristic
random variable,

00:04:35.890 --> 00:04:44.130
is a random variable whose
range or possible values

00:04:44.130 --> 00:04:47.910
is just 0 and 1.

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:50.030
So it's a random variable
where the real numbers

00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:53.140
are 0, 1 that you assign
to every sample point.

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:56.920
And it's called a characteristic
or indicator random variable

00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:00.660
because it indicates
which sample points have

00:05:00.660 --> 00:05:02.430
a certain property.

00:05:02.430 --> 00:05:05.480
In this case, all the
coins were the same.

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:07.310
Or it indicates
that a sample point

00:05:07.310 --> 00:05:09.110
has a certain
characteristic, which

00:05:09.110 --> 00:05:11.742
is why it's called a
characteristic random variable.

00:05:11.742 --> 00:05:13.200
And we're going to
be talking a lot

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:14.800
about these kinds
of random variables

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:17.760
over the next couple of weeks.

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:21.440
Now, in general, a random
variable is equivalent to,

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:26.470
or it can define a partition
on the sample space.

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:29.710
For an indicator
random variable,

00:05:29.710 --> 00:05:33.220
it defines a partition
with two blocks.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:38.470
For example, say we look at the
sample space with three coin

00:05:38.470 --> 00:05:41.080
tosses there.

00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:42.180
There's eight outcomes.

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:50.400
There's heads, heads,
heads; heads, tails, heads;

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:55.556
heads, heads, tails;
tail, heads, heads;

00:05:55.556 --> 00:05:56.835
and the reverse of those.

00:06:04.470 --> 00:06:07.180
This is the sample space
when I toss three coins.

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:09.940
There's eight possible outcomes.

00:06:09.940 --> 00:06:12.845
The random variable M
defines this partition.

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:20.790
Up top, you have M equals 1, and
down below you have M equals 0.

00:06:20.790 --> 00:06:23.450
Because these are the outcomes
where all the coins match.

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:24.700
These are the ones that don't.

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:30.775
The random variable R defines
a different partition.

00:06:33.740 --> 00:06:38.320
In that case, the
partition has four blocks.

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:44.860
Here is R equals 0, no heads.

00:06:44.860 --> 00:06:48.660
This is R equals 1, to one head.

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:51.340
R equals 2, and R equals 3.

00:06:54.460 --> 00:06:58.750
So a random variable just sort
of organizes your sample space,

00:06:58.750 --> 00:07:01.450
partitions it into
blocks, defined

00:07:01.450 --> 00:07:03.560
by all the elements
in the block,

00:07:03.560 --> 00:07:05.976
the outcomes in the
block have the same value

00:07:05.976 --> 00:07:06.975
for the random variable.

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:14.000
And, in fact, every
block is really an event.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.040
In particular, we
can say that, if you

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:21.530
look at the outcomes for
which the random variable

00:07:21.530 --> 00:07:24.830
on that outcome
equals some value x,

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:32.160
this is simply the
event that R equals x.

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:34.900
The random variable is x.

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:37.490
And, of course, an event is just
a subset of the sample space.

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:40.345
It's a collection of outcomes
that define the event.

00:07:42.890 --> 00:07:45.870
And since we know we could talk
about probabilities of events,

00:07:45.870 --> 00:07:47.900
we can now say things like this.

00:07:47.900 --> 00:07:52.610
We can say the probability
that a random variable equals

00:07:52.610 --> 00:07:57.950
x is simply the probability
of that event happening, which

00:07:57.950 --> 00:08:03.890
is the sum over all outcomes
for which the random variable

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:08.850
equals x for that outcome,
summing its probability.

00:08:08.850 --> 00:08:12.060
So the probability that the
random variable equals a value

00:08:12.060 --> 00:08:14.500
is the sum of the probabilities
of the sample points

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:17.500
for which R has that value.

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:19.250
All right, this is all
really basic stuff,

00:08:19.250 --> 00:08:23.200
but important to get down.

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:26.960
So, for example,
what's the probability

00:08:26.960 --> 00:08:31.372
that R equals 2 in our
case with the three coins?

00:08:31.372 --> 00:08:35.090
You flip three coins-- let's say
the coins are fair and mutually

00:08:35.090 --> 00:08:35.860
independent.

00:08:35.860 --> 00:08:38.720
We probably need to know that.

00:08:38.720 --> 00:08:41.675
What is the
probability R equals 2?

00:08:41.675 --> 00:08:42.950
AUDIENCE: 3/8?

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:47.780
PROFESSOR: 3/8, because you've
got three outcomes, each

00:08:47.780 --> 00:08:50.050
with a probability 1/8.

00:08:50.050 --> 00:08:52.590
All right, so by
this definition, that

00:08:52.590 --> 00:08:56.640
would be the same as the
probability of heads, heads,

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:01.240
tails; heads, tails,
heads; tails, heads,

00:09:01.240 --> 00:09:03.160
heads; that's 3/8.

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:10.660
What's the probability
that M equals 1?

00:09:16.928 --> 00:09:19.300
What's the probability
that M equals 1?

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:23.050
M is 1 if all the coins match.

00:09:23.050 --> 00:09:27.360
1/4 because you've got two
cases there-- heads, heads,

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:31.720
heads-- whoops--
or tails, tails,

00:09:31.720 --> 00:09:36.982
tails; and that's 2/8, or 1/4.

00:09:36.982 --> 00:09:39.840
Now we can also talk
about the probability

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:43.930
that a random variable
is in some range.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:47.180
For example, I could ask,
what's the probability

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:49.925
that R is at least 2?

00:09:52.525 --> 00:09:58.340
All right, that would mean the
sum i equals 2 to infinity,

00:09:58.340 --> 00:10:02.230
the probability R equals i.

00:10:02.230 --> 00:10:03.035
And what is that?

00:10:05.930 --> 00:10:07.150
What's the probability?

00:10:07.150 --> 00:10:09.740
R is at least 2.

00:10:09.740 --> 00:10:10.480
1/2.

00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:12.469
It's the probability
that R equals 2,

00:10:12.469 --> 00:10:14.010
plus the probability
that R equals 3.

00:10:14.010 --> 00:10:16.840
There's four outcomes there,
each with 1/8, so that's 1/2.

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:24.030
And finally, we can talk
about the probability

00:10:24.030 --> 00:10:28.770
that R is in some set of values.

00:10:28.770 --> 00:10:34.670
So we could say, for
example, for any subset

00:10:34.670 --> 00:10:38.830
of the real numbers, we
define the probability

00:10:38.830 --> 00:10:44.100
that R attains a value
in that set is simply

00:10:44.100 --> 00:10:50.660
the sum over all possible
values in the set,

00:10:50.660 --> 00:10:52.570
that the probability
R equals that value.

00:10:55.570 --> 00:11:00.170
So we could ask, what's the
probability that, say, we

00:11:00.170 --> 00:11:04.950
take A being the set 1, 3.

00:11:04.950 --> 00:11:08.120
I could ask for
the probability R

00:11:08.120 --> 00:11:13.380
is A when it's 1, 3, which is
the same as the probability

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:15.220
R is odd.

00:11:15.220 --> 00:11:18.210
Because Our could
only be 0, 1, 2, or 3.

00:11:18.210 --> 00:11:24.494
What's the probability R
is odd in this example?

00:11:24.494 --> 00:11:26.410
Flip three coins, we're
asking the probability

00:11:26.410 --> 00:11:31.240
you get an odd number of
heads-- one or three heads.

00:11:31.240 --> 00:11:32.650
1/2.

00:11:32.650 --> 00:11:40.057
Again, you've got four sample
points-- here and there.

00:11:40.057 --> 00:11:40.640
So that's 1/2.

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:48.125
All right, any questions
about the definition?

00:11:51.210 --> 00:11:54.130
All right, now, we're only
going to worry about the case

00:11:54.130 --> 00:11:58.100
when random variables
are discrete.

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:02.940
Namely, there's a
finite number of values.

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:05.190
If you have continuous random
variables, which they'll

00:12:05.190 --> 00:12:06.550
deal with in other
courses, instead

00:12:06.550 --> 00:12:08.010
of doing sums and
stuff like that,

00:12:08.010 --> 00:12:09.260
you're working with integrals.

00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:12.840
But for this course, it's
going to be all countable sets,

00:12:12.840 --> 00:12:16.770
and usually often finite sets.

00:12:16.770 --> 00:12:21.300
Now, conditional probability
carries over very nicely

00:12:21.300 --> 00:12:22.690
to random variables as well.

00:12:22.690 --> 00:12:27.160
For example, we could
write down the probability

00:12:27.160 --> 00:12:33.974
that R equals 2 given that M
equals 1, where R and M are

00:12:33.974 --> 00:12:36.140
the same random variables
we've been looking at when

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:38.340
you flip the three coins.

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:40.830
What is that probability?

00:12:40.830 --> 00:12:43.960
0, the probability of getting
exactly two heads when they're

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:46.210
all the same, can't happen.

00:12:46.210 --> 00:12:46.990
It's 0.

00:12:46.990 --> 00:12:50.590
You can either have
three heads or no heads.

00:12:50.590 --> 00:12:51.380
So that's 0.

00:12:54.920 --> 00:12:57.852
The notion of independence
also carries over

00:12:57.852 --> 00:12:59.310
to random variables,
but you've got

00:12:59.310 --> 00:13:00.530
to be a little careful here.

00:13:06.670 --> 00:13:12.870
Two random variables,
R1 and R2, are

00:13:12.870 --> 00:13:26.070
said to be independent if-- and
this is a little complicated--

00:13:26.070 --> 00:13:31.392
for all possible
values, x1 and x2

00:13:31.392 --> 00:13:40.290
in the real numbers, the
probability that R1 is x1,

00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:46.580
given that R2 is x2, is the
same as the probability of R1

00:13:46.580 --> 00:13:48.910
equals x1 not knowing
anything about R2.

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:57.610
Or there's a special case
when this can't happen.

00:13:57.610 --> 00:14:02.190
Namely, the probability
that R2 equals x2 is 0.

00:14:05.020 --> 00:14:08.830
So, for two random
variables to be independent,

00:14:08.830 --> 00:14:12.720
it needs to be the case that,
no matter what happens out here

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:15.910
with R2, and whatever
you know about it,

00:14:15.910 --> 00:14:19.740
it can't influence
the probability for R1

00:14:19.740 --> 00:14:22.030
to equal anything.

00:14:22.030 --> 00:14:27.790
So no value of R2
influences any value of R1.

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:31.180
So it's the strongest possible
thing with independence

00:14:31.180 --> 00:14:33.946
for it to apply to
random variables.

00:14:33.946 --> 00:14:36.570
And there's an
equivalent definition,

00:14:36.570 --> 00:14:39.260
and we're going to use these
interchangeably, just as there

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:43.010
were two definitions for
independence of events,

00:14:43.010 --> 00:14:45.840
there's the product for them.

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:48.890
So the equivalent
definitions says

00:14:48.890 --> 00:14:55.500
for all x1 and x2 in the
real numbers, the probability

00:14:55.500 --> 00:15:02.550
that R1 equals x1 and
R2 equals x2 is simply

00:15:02.550 --> 00:15:05.680
the product of
those probabilities.

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:12.410
Probability R1 equals x1 times
the probability R2 equals x2.

00:15:15.029 --> 00:15:16.820
And you don't have to
worry about that case

00:15:16.820 --> 00:15:19.980
where R2 being x2 is 0.

00:15:19.980 --> 00:15:24.490
So we can use both of those
as definitions of independence

00:15:24.490 --> 00:15:27.550
of random variables.

00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:29.430
All right, so let's
see an example.

00:15:29.430 --> 00:15:33.500
We've got R and M. We've talked
about two random variables.

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:36.320
Are they independent
random variables?

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:42.790
M is the indicated
random variable

00:15:42.790 --> 00:15:44.630
for all the coins matching.

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:47.180
R is the random variable
that tells us how many heads

00:15:47.180 --> 00:15:49.210
there were in three coins.

00:15:49.210 --> 00:15:50.790
Are they independent?

00:15:50.790 --> 00:15:51.510
AUDIENCE: No.

00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:54.024
PROFESSOR: No, why not?

00:15:54.024 --> 00:15:57.293
AUDIENCE: Because information
with what one is narrows down

00:15:57.293 --> 00:15:57.934
[INAUDIBLE].

00:15:57.934 --> 00:15:59.100
PROFESSOR: Yes, that's true.

00:15:59.100 --> 00:16:01.560
Information about
what one value is

00:16:01.560 --> 00:16:04.210
influences the probability
that the other guy

00:16:04.210 --> 00:16:05.240
has a certain value.

00:16:05.240 --> 00:16:09.030
In particular, we can
find a case of x1 and x2

00:16:09.030 --> 00:16:11.020
where this fails.

00:16:11.020 --> 00:16:12.910
One case would be
the probability

00:16:12.910 --> 00:16:21.036
of what we've already done,
that R equals 2 and M equals 1.

00:16:21.036 --> 00:16:23.930
What was this probability?

00:16:23.930 --> 00:16:24.650
0.

00:16:24.650 --> 00:16:26.780
If everything matches,
you can't have two heads.

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:28.110
That's 0.

00:16:28.110 --> 00:16:31.220
That does not equal
the probability

00:16:31.220 --> 00:16:36.580
of two heads times the
probability they all match.

00:16:36.580 --> 00:16:40.550
Because this probability,
two heads is 3/8,

00:16:40.550 --> 00:16:43.045
probability they
all match is 1/4.

00:16:43.045 --> 00:16:47.510
And 3/8 times a 1/4 is not 0.

00:16:47.510 --> 00:16:49.730
So R and M are not independent.

00:16:57.470 --> 00:17:00.560
OK, now in general to
show two random variables

00:17:00.560 --> 00:17:03.070
are not independent,
all you gotta

00:17:03.070 --> 00:17:08.180
do is find one pair of [? out ?]
values for which there's

00:17:08.180 --> 00:17:09.700
dependence.

00:17:09.700 --> 00:17:12.060
To show their
independent, you've

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:15.390
got to deal with all
possible pairs of values.

00:17:15.390 --> 00:17:17.480
So it's harder show
independence in general.

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:24.588
All right, let's
do another example,

00:17:24.588 --> 00:17:26.569
get a little practice with this.

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:51.730
Say we have two fair independent
six-sided die, normal dice.

00:17:51.730 --> 00:17:54.590
And the outcome of
the first one is D1,

00:17:54.590 --> 00:17:58.710
and the outcome of
the second roll is D2.

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:04.170
And by independent, I mean here
that knowing any information

00:18:04.170 --> 00:18:06.040
about what the second
die is does not

00:18:06.040 --> 00:18:09.020
give you any change
in your probability

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:12.690
that the first
die has any value.

00:18:12.690 --> 00:18:15.500
And now we define
another value, S,

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:19.825
to be D1 plus D2,
the sum of the dice.

00:18:22.490 --> 00:18:23.930
Is S a random variable?

00:18:27.920 --> 00:18:32.190
Yeah, for any outcome-- an
outcome being a pair of dice

00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:36.026
values-- it maps that
outcome to a real number,

00:18:36.026 --> 00:18:41.700
a number between 2 and 12, OK?

00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:43.560
Let's do another one.

00:18:43.560 --> 00:18:53.870
Let's let T be 1 if S is 7,
namely the sum of the dice

00:18:53.870 --> 00:18:55.200
is 7, and 0 otherwise.

00:18:59.860 --> 00:19:02.340
T is also a random variable.

00:19:02.340 --> 00:19:05.030
In fact, what kind is it?

00:19:05.030 --> 00:19:08.550
Yeah, indicator,
characteristic, whatever.

00:19:08.550 --> 00:19:13.830
It's telling you if the sum
of the dice is 7 or not.

00:19:13.830 --> 00:19:18.300
All right, now, there's
four random variables here.

00:19:18.300 --> 00:19:21.440
Each die, which we
already have told you,

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:23.370
we're assuming are independent.

00:19:23.370 --> 00:19:26.830
The sum and the indicator
if the sum is 7.

00:19:30.130 --> 00:19:34.990
All right, what about
these two values?

00:19:34.990 --> 00:19:38.170
Are D1, the first die,
and the sum independent?

00:19:41.603 --> 00:19:43.998
AUDIENCE: No?

00:19:43.998 --> 00:19:45.440
No?

00:19:45.440 --> 00:19:47.850
PROFESSOR: No,
intuitively they're not.

00:19:47.850 --> 00:19:52.020
Because if I know something
about the first die,

00:19:52.020 --> 00:19:55.710
I probably know
something about the sum.

00:19:55.710 --> 00:19:59.110
Now to really nail
that down, you've

00:19:59.110 --> 00:20:02.670
got to give me a
value for this, which

00:20:02.670 --> 00:20:07.419
influences the probability
that obtains some value, right?

00:20:07.419 --> 00:20:09.710
That's how you would convince
me that, in fact, they're

00:20:09.710 --> 00:20:10.209
dependent.

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:15.870
Can anybody give
me a value for this

00:20:15.870 --> 00:20:18.770
that changes the probability
this equals something?

00:20:23.320 --> 00:20:24.250
AUDIENCE: Guess?

00:20:24.250 --> 00:20:27.330
If it's like 1, then
[INAUDIBLE] has to be 6.

00:20:27.330 --> 00:20:32.170
PROFESSOR: If this is
1, what value of this

00:20:32.170 --> 00:20:35.028
could be influenced?

00:20:35.028 --> 00:20:39.930
AUDIENCE: You know that in order
for-- the only set of values

00:20:39.930 --> 00:20:44.348
S can take now, it can only
be from 1 to-- from 2 to 7.

00:20:44.348 --> 00:20:45.306
PROFESSOR: From 2 to 7.

00:20:45.306 --> 00:20:49.230
In particular now,
this can't be 12.

00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:51.570
So what I could do is say
the probability that S

00:20:51.570 --> 00:20:58.780
equals 12 and the first die
was 1, what's that probability?

00:20:58.780 --> 00:20:59.280
AUDIENCE: 0.

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:01.300
PROFESSOR: 0.

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:03.980
And that does not
equal the probability

00:21:03.980 --> 00:21:08.380
S is 12 times the probability
the first die was 1.

00:21:11.240 --> 00:21:13.690
Or we could plug it into
the other definition.

00:21:13.690 --> 00:21:18.290
The probability that S equals
12 given the first die is 1

00:21:18.290 --> 00:21:21.440
is not equal to the
probability S equals 12.

00:21:21.440 --> 00:21:24.510
And, in fact, probability
the first die is 1 is not 0.

00:21:24.510 --> 00:21:26.750
So either definition,
of course, works

00:21:26.750 --> 00:21:29.630
to show that they are dependent.

00:21:29.630 --> 00:21:31.350
So S and D1 are dependent.

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:38.430
All you need is
one possible pair

00:21:38.430 --> 00:21:40.360
of values to show dependence.

00:21:40.360 --> 00:21:41.660
That's usually easy to do.

00:21:46.350 --> 00:21:52.700
All right, what about
D1, the first die, and T,

00:21:52.700 --> 00:21:55.695
the indicator for getting a 7?

00:21:59.150 --> 00:22:03.310
Are D1 and T independent
random variables?

00:22:05.815 --> 00:22:08.860
All right, somebody's
shaking their head no.

00:22:08.860 --> 00:22:12.430
They seem to be dependent
because knowing the first die

00:22:12.430 --> 00:22:15.660
seems like it should tell you
something about the probability

00:22:15.660 --> 00:22:19.930
of getting a 7 for the sum.

00:22:19.930 --> 00:22:22.140
That's a good first intuition.

00:22:22.140 --> 00:22:23.770
In fact, you always
want to assume

00:22:23.770 --> 00:22:27.070
things are dependent unless you
convince yourself otherwise.

00:22:27.070 --> 00:22:29.770
It's always a good rule.

00:22:29.770 --> 00:22:34.200
Now, in fact, in this
case, it is independent.

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:37.910
The probability of getting
a 7 is not, it turns out,

00:22:37.910 --> 00:22:41.540
influenced by the first die.

00:22:41.540 --> 00:22:44.380
Anything else would
be, but 7 is not.

00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:45.827
Let's see why that is.

00:22:45.827 --> 00:22:47.660
And to do that, we'd
actually have to check,

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:51.700
I think, 12 cases, all
possible values for D1 and T,

00:22:51.700 --> 00:22:54.710
but you'll get the
idea pretty quick.

00:22:54.710 --> 00:22:59.620
The probability that T
equals 1, namely you got a 7,

00:22:59.620 --> 00:23:00.970
given that D1 equals 1.

00:23:00.970 --> 00:23:03.180
What's that?

00:23:03.180 --> 00:23:06.965
The probability of getting 7
for the sum given your first die

00:23:06.965 --> 00:23:08.760
is a 1, what's that probability?

00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:09.540
AUDIENCE: 1/6?

00:23:09.540 --> 00:23:13.730
PROFESSOR: 1/6, because the
second one better be a 6.

00:23:13.730 --> 00:23:19.500
All right, and what's the
probability T equals 1?

00:23:19.500 --> 00:23:21.425
What's the probability
of rolling a 7?

00:23:24.810 --> 00:23:26.096
Yeah?

00:23:26.096 --> 00:23:27.240
AUDIENCE: 6/36.

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:28.670
PROFESSOR: 6/36.

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:30.160
There's six ways to do it.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:35.880
1 and 6, 2 and 5, 3 and 4, 4
and 3, 5 and 2, and 6 and 1,

00:23:35.880 --> 00:23:39.370
out of 36 possibilities
equally likely.

00:23:39.370 --> 00:23:42.670
So that worked here.

00:23:42.670 --> 00:23:46.240
Now probability of getting
a 7 given the second

00:23:46.240 --> 00:23:49.605
die-- sorry-- the
first die is a 2.

00:23:49.605 --> 00:23:50.105
What's that?

00:23:53.740 --> 00:23:58.310
Probability of getting a 7 given
that your first die is a 2.

00:23:58.310 --> 00:24:02.720
1/6, because you've got to
have the second die be a 5,

00:24:02.720 --> 00:24:05.670
and that happens 1/6.

00:24:05.670 --> 00:24:08.740
And that equals the right thing.

00:24:08.740 --> 00:24:11.800
In fact, I can
keep on going here.

00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:18.560
Probability T equals 1,
given D1 is anything, 6.

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:20.450
Well, for every
value of D1, there's

00:24:20.450 --> 00:24:25.690
exactly one value of
D2 that adds to a 7.

00:24:25.690 --> 00:24:31.060
So it's still 1/6, which is
the probability of getting

00:24:31.060 --> 00:24:33.770
the 7 in the first place.

00:24:33.770 --> 00:24:38.700
Now we've also got to check
the probability T equals 0,

00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:40.910
given all these cases for D1.

00:24:40.910 --> 00:24:43.340
D1 equals 1.

00:24:43.340 --> 00:24:43.850
What's this?

00:24:43.850 --> 00:24:46.970
The probability of not getting
a 7 given the first die is a 1.

00:24:46.970 --> 00:24:49.875
What's that?

00:24:49.875 --> 00:24:50.780
AUDIENCE: 5/6.

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:53.820
PROFESSOR: 5/6, it's the
opposite of this case.

00:24:53.820 --> 00:24:54.460
They pair up.

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:59.300
That's got to be 5/6,
and that is, of course,

00:24:59.300 --> 00:25:02.960
the probability of T equals 0.

00:25:02.960 --> 00:25:07.810
And the same is true for
all the other five cases.

00:25:07.810 --> 00:25:14.200
The probability T equals
0 given any value of D

00:25:14.200 --> 00:25:19.910
is 5/6, which equals, the
probability T equals 0.

00:25:19.910 --> 00:25:22.860
So we check all
possible values of T1

00:25:22.860 --> 00:25:25.710
and all possible ways of
D1, and lo and behold,

00:25:25.710 --> 00:25:28.050
it works every time.

00:25:28.050 --> 00:25:29.840
So knowing the
first die does not

00:25:29.840 --> 00:25:33.630
change the probability
of getting a 7.

00:25:33.630 --> 00:25:35.595
Would it change the
probability of getting a 6?

00:25:38.150 --> 00:25:41.040
Yeah, because if the
first die were a 6,

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:42.960
you know you're going
to get more than a 6.

00:25:42.960 --> 00:25:46.000
So it just holds
true because I picked

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:49.220
it to be an indicator for 7.

00:25:49.220 --> 00:25:52.780
Any questions about that?

00:25:52.780 --> 00:25:56.900
So if you're ever asked to
show things are independent,

00:25:56.900 --> 00:25:59.424
you've got to go
through all the cases.

00:25:59.424 --> 00:26:01.090
If you're asked to
show their dependent,

00:26:01.090 --> 00:26:06.830
just find one case that
blows it up, and you're done.

00:26:06.830 --> 00:26:10.090
OK, you can also talk
about independence

00:26:10.090 --> 00:26:12.466
for many random variables.

00:26:12.466 --> 00:26:14.340
And you have a notion
of mutual independence.

00:26:26.900 --> 00:26:30.080
And this is a little hairy.

00:26:30.080 --> 00:26:32.090
It's a natural thing.

00:26:32.090 --> 00:26:54.400
R1, R2, up to Rn are mutually
independent if for all

00:26:54.400 --> 00:27:00.430
the values of all the random
variables, so x1, x2, xn.

00:27:03.941 --> 00:27:06.190
And we're going to give the
product form, because it's

00:27:06.190 --> 00:27:08.650
the simpler way to do it here.

00:27:08.650 --> 00:27:19.170
The probability that R1 is
x1, and R2 is x2, and Rn is xn

00:27:19.170 --> 00:27:21.450
equals the product of the
individual probabilities.

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:35.420
It's the natural generalization
for two variables.

00:27:35.420 --> 00:27:37.950
And there's also
the equivalent form

00:27:37.950 --> 00:27:40.665
in conditional probabilities,
but that's a little harrier

00:27:40.665 --> 00:27:43.710
to write down, and we
generally don't work with that.

00:27:49.880 --> 00:27:54.340
Any questions about
mutual independence?

00:27:54.340 --> 00:27:55.227
Yeah.

00:27:55.227 --> 00:27:56.143
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:04.173 --> 00:28:05.664
PROFESSOR: So any subset what?

00:28:05.664 --> 00:28:06.580
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:09.860 --> 00:28:11.720
PROFESSOR: Yes, in
the conditional form

00:28:11.720 --> 00:28:15.770
you check any subset,
here you don't have

00:28:15.770 --> 00:28:16.940
to worry about the subsets.

00:28:16.940 --> 00:28:20.550
You take any possible
value for all of them,

00:28:20.550 --> 00:28:24.290
so there's no subset
notation in this version,

00:28:24.290 --> 00:28:25.706
so you can do without it.

00:28:25.706 --> 00:28:27.080
That would be
equivalent, there's

00:28:27.080 --> 00:28:29.371
another form where you look
at all the possible subsets

00:28:29.371 --> 00:28:31.030
as well, and
conditioning on that.

00:28:31.030 --> 00:28:32.932
But this is good enough,
and this is probably

00:28:32.932 --> 00:28:34.890
the simplest way to do
the mutual independence,

00:28:34.890 --> 00:28:36.150
is like this.

00:28:36.150 --> 00:28:38.850
So every variable
is included here.

00:28:38.850 --> 00:28:41.950
And that will imply the
same thing for any subset.

00:28:41.950 --> 00:28:45.380
You don't have to check
every subset here.

00:28:45.380 --> 00:28:47.620
And then you could do
that by just summing

00:28:47.620 --> 00:28:51.560
over Rn being everything,
and that cancels away

00:28:51.560 --> 00:28:53.016
to get rid of items.

00:28:53.016 --> 00:28:54.640
But you don't have
to worry about that.

00:28:58.020 --> 00:29:00.540
OK, so we're going to
change gears a little bit

00:29:00.540 --> 00:29:06.990
now, and talk about the
probability distribution

00:29:06.990 --> 00:29:10.600
function, which is just
a way a sort of writing

00:29:10.600 --> 00:29:14.860
down or characterizing the
probabilities associated

00:29:14.860 --> 00:29:16.625
with each value being attained.

00:29:21.920 --> 00:29:33.690
So given a random variable,
R, the probability

00:29:33.690 --> 00:29:53.360
also known as the point,
distribution function,

00:29:53.360 --> 00:30:01.580
also denoted pdf, probability
distribution function, for R

00:30:01.580 --> 00:30:03.700
is, well, it's very simple.

00:30:03.700 --> 00:30:07.940
It's just the function
f of x, which equals

00:30:07.940 --> 00:30:11.320
the probability that R is x.

00:30:11.320 --> 00:30:12.940
Very simple.

00:30:12.940 --> 00:30:17.170
But now we're characterizing
it as a function.

00:30:17.170 --> 00:30:20.320
And there's also a notion of
the cumulative distribution

00:30:20.320 --> 00:30:24.830
function, which is going to
be the probability that R

00:30:24.830 --> 00:30:27.130
is less than or equal to x.

00:30:27.130 --> 00:30:28.231
Let's write that down.

00:30:52.800 --> 00:31:12.500
The cumulative
distribution function F

00:31:12.500 --> 00:31:19.820
for random variable
R is simply f

00:31:19.820 --> 00:31:25.840
of x is the probability that
R is at most x, which is just

00:31:25.840 --> 00:31:30.730
the sum over all y
less than or equal to x

00:31:30.730 --> 00:31:32.510
the probability R equals y.

00:31:35.480 --> 00:31:40.930
So the distribution functions
characterize the probability

00:31:40.930 --> 00:31:43.560
a random variable
takes on any value,

00:31:43.560 --> 00:31:47.400
and there's certain common ones
that just come up all the time.

00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:49.190
And so people have
done a lot of analysis

00:31:49.190 --> 00:31:52.990
about them because they
occur so frequently.

00:31:52.990 --> 00:31:56.110
And we're going to talk
about three of them today.

00:32:02.830 --> 00:32:06.860
The first is really
simple, and that

00:32:06.860 --> 00:32:10.000
is the Bernoulli
random variable,

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:11.820
or indicator random variable.

00:32:14.430 --> 00:32:29.520
All right, so for an indicator
random variable, f 0 is p,

00:32:29.520 --> 00:32:36.290
and f 1 is 1 minus p, for sum p.

00:32:36.290 --> 00:32:38.817
The probability could be half,
if you're flipping a coin.

00:32:38.817 --> 00:32:41.400
The probability of heads could
be a half, probability of tails

00:32:41.400 --> 00:32:42.066
would be a half.

00:32:42.066 --> 00:32:45.360
It's just two values, 0 and 1.

00:32:45.360 --> 00:32:48.770
And then the cumulative
function is very simple.

00:32:48.770 --> 00:32:53.130
F 0 is p, big F of 1 is 1.

00:32:55.710 --> 00:32:58.225
So that is about as simple
of functions as you can get.

00:33:03.670 --> 00:33:07.390
The next simplest,
and also very common,

00:33:07.390 --> 00:33:10.370
is called a uniform
random variable.

00:33:14.970 --> 00:33:16.380
Let's define that.

00:33:26.300 --> 00:33:32.610
For a uniform random
variable-- and we

00:33:32.610 --> 00:33:35.000
have to define what
it's defined on--

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:42.900
on say the integers from 1 to n,
every value is equally likely.

00:33:42.900 --> 00:33:46.600
All the integers from 1 to n
are equally likely to occur.

00:33:46.600 --> 00:33:51.470
And so in this case, n is a
parameter of the function.

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:54.750
fn of K is simply 1/n.

00:33:54.750 --> 00:33:57.860
Each integer from 1 to
n is equally likely.

00:33:57.860 --> 00:33:59.260
So it's 1 and n.

00:34:03.990 --> 00:34:06.360
All right, what is the
cumulative distribution

00:34:06.360 --> 00:34:08.920
function for this?

00:34:08.920 --> 00:34:13.989
What is big F of n
of K for the uniform?

00:34:13.989 --> 00:34:18.350
The probability that
the random variable

00:34:18.350 --> 00:34:22.518
takes a value that's at most K?

00:34:22.518 --> 00:34:24.449
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:34:24.449 --> 00:34:27.199
PROFESSOR: Close, K/n.

00:34:27.199 --> 00:34:30.139
And you could
think of K being 1.

00:34:30.139 --> 00:34:33.469
You have a least the
1 over n probability.

00:34:33.469 --> 00:34:35.290
So you have K chances.

00:34:35.290 --> 00:34:40.159
It could be 1, 2, 3, 4 up
to K, each has a 1/n chance.

00:34:40.159 --> 00:34:42.380
Because we've got,
the definition

00:34:42.380 --> 00:34:47.469
is less than or
equal, not less than.

00:34:51.020 --> 00:34:53.250
Uniform distributions
come up all the time,

00:34:53.250 --> 00:34:59.460
rolling a fair die is uniform
on 1 through 6 for values.

00:34:59.460 --> 00:35:02.560
If I pick a random student
in the class, the chance

00:35:02.560 --> 00:35:05.940
I pick you is 1 in
the size of the class.

00:35:05.940 --> 00:35:07.520
We have uniform sample spaces.

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:12.300
Each outcome occurs
equally likely.

00:35:12.300 --> 00:35:16.340
All right, any
questions about uniform?

00:35:16.340 --> 00:35:18.552
[INAUDIBLE]

00:35:18.552 --> 00:35:20.260
OK, so while we're
talking about uniform,

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:24.970
I want to play a
game, whose optimal

00:35:24.970 --> 00:35:26.980
strategy is going to
turn out to be related

00:35:26.980 --> 00:35:30.120
to uniform distributions.

00:35:30.120 --> 00:35:33.750
Now the game works as follows.

00:35:33.750 --> 00:35:37.890
I'm going to have
two envelopes here.

00:35:37.890 --> 00:35:42.400
And inside each envelope,
I've written a number.

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:45.060
And the number in
this case is a number

00:35:45.060 --> 00:35:47.155
between 0 and 100 inclusive.

00:35:50.710 --> 00:35:54.090
It's not a random number,
because I wrote it,

00:35:54.090 --> 00:35:56.600
and maybe I'm not
such a nice guy.

00:35:56.600 --> 00:35:59.230
I might have picked nasty
numbers to write here.

00:35:59.230 --> 00:36:00.910
They are different, though.

00:36:00.910 --> 00:36:04.060
The numbers are different
in the envelopes.

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:07.260
Now I'm going to pick a
volunteer from the class,

00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:10.630
and their job is to pick
the envelope with the bigger

00:36:10.630 --> 00:36:12.200
number.

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:14.910
And if they get the one
with the bigger number,

00:36:14.910 --> 00:36:19.520
then they get one of
these guys for ice cream.

00:36:19.520 --> 00:36:22.910
And if they don't get the
one with the bigger number,

00:36:22.910 --> 00:36:27.340
they get the nerd
pride pocket protector.

00:36:27.340 --> 00:36:31.030
Now, since you don't know
which number I put in which,

00:36:31.030 --> 00:36:35.520
50-50 if you get the prize,
the $10 gift certificate.

00:36:35.520 --> 00:36:37.980
So to give you a
little bit of an edge,

00:36:37.980 --> 00:36:41.060
I'm going to let you
open one of the envelopes

00:36:41.060 --> 00:36:43.320
and see what number's there.

00:36:43.320 --> 00:36:46.780
Then you have to decide, do
you want the number you got,

00:36:46.780 --> 00:36:50.210
or do you want the
other envelope?

00:36:50.210 --> 00:36:52.330
OK?

