What's the probability
to assign to that chance,

00:50:33.690 --> 00:50:36.925
that you guessed low?

00:50:36.925 --> 00:50:39.547
You could use the value
of y in your answer.

00:50:39.547 --> 00:50:41.630
You don't know y, but we
can write it on the tree.

00:50:44.790 --> 00:50:47.686
What if y was 1?

00:50:47.686 --> 00:50:49.185
The smallest number
in the envelopes

00:50:49.185 --> 00:50:54.310
is one, what's the probability
you guessed below 1?

00:50:57.660 --> 00:51:02.950
Not quite 0, one of your
possible end guesses

00:51:02.950 --> 00:51:05.920
would be too low,
namely, a half.

00:51:05.920 --> 00:51:10.170
If the smallest number
y were 2, what's

00:51:10.170 --> 00:51:13.340
the probability
you guess below 2?

00:51:13.340 --> 00:51:15.070
2/n.

00:51:15.070 --> 00:51:19.510
And in general, if y
is the smallest value,

00:51:19.510 --> 00:51:21.440
you've got y possible
guesses that it

00:51:21.440 --> 00:51:27.070
would be too low, namely all
the half integers less than y.

00:51:27.070 --> 00:51:31.920
So the probability
you guess low is y/n,

00:51:31.920 --> 00:51:34.190
because each one
is 1 in n chance.

00:51:34.190 --> 00:51:37.250
And there's y that are too low.

00:51:37.250 --> 00:51:39.070
What's the probability
your guess is good,

00:51:39.070 --> 00:51:40.430
that you split y and z?

00:51:44.930 --> 00:51:52.310
z minus y over n, because
they're-- between these

00:51:52.310 --> 00:51:56.910
integers, z and y, there's
z minus y half integers.

00:51:56.910 --> 00:51:59.792
Each could have been guessed
with probability 1/n.

00:51:59.792 --> 00:52:01.625
And what's the probability
you guessed high?

00:52:04.330 --> 00:52:07.560
n minus z over n,
because there's

00:52:07.560 --> 00:52:11.856
n minus g half
integers between z

00:52:11.856 --> 00:52:16.570
and n being the last possible
one, and minus the half there.

00:52:16.570 --> 00:52:19.620
All right, so we've
got the first branch.

00:52:19.620 --> 00:52:24.620
Now the next branch
is the revealed value.

00:52:24.620 --> 00:52:29.190
Did you open the smaller
one or the larger one?

00:52:29.190 --> 00:52:31.430
r equals y means you
opened the smaller one.

00:52:31.430 --> 00:52:33.300
r equals z means you
saw the bigger one.

00:52:42.580 --> 00:52:44.995
All right, if I've gone
down this branch where

00:52:44.995 --> 00:52:47.750
I guessed too low, but
I don't know that, yet,

00:52:47.750 --> 00:52:49.880
but say I've guessed
too low, what's

00:52:49.880 --> 00:52:52.120
the probability I opened
the smaller envelope?

00:52:55.830 --> 00:52:58.500
One half, because you're just
picking a random envelope

00:52:58.500 --> 00:52:59.870
and opening up.

00:52:59.870 --> 00:53:02.790
So these each happen
with probability a half.

00:53:02.790 --> 00:53:05.066
And that's true no matter what.

00:53:05.066 --> 00:53:05.940
They're all one half.

00:53:08.530 --> 00:53:13.370
All right, well, now we
can compute the probability

00:53:13.370 --> 00:53:14.910
of each outcome.

00:53:14.910 --> 00:53:19.490
This is y/n times
1/2, is y over 2n.

00:53:19.490 --> 00:53:22.920
This is y over 2n also.

00:53:22.920 --> 00:53:24.880
This is z minus y over 2n.

00:53:27.742 --> 00:53:31.090
z minus y over 2n.

00:53:31.090 --> 00:53:32.910
n minus z over 2n.

00:53:39.298 --> 00:53:42.030
All right, I got all
the sample points.

00:53:42.030 --> 00:53:45.530
I got all the probabilities.

00:53:45.530 --> 00:53:46.872
Let's figure out if you win now.

00:53:46.872 --> 00:53:49.080
And to do that, the first
thing we have to figure out

00:53:49.080 --> 00:53:49.995
is, do you swap?

00:53:52.650 --> 00:53:54.073
Do you swap here?

00:53:58.627 --> 00:53:59.460
Well, what happened?

00:53:59.460 --> 00:54:04.240
I revealed y, which is
bigger than my split value

00:54:04.240 --> 00:54:06.270
x, my guessed value.

00:54:06.270 --> 00:54:10.890
And so I am guessing I've
got the biggest value.

00:54:10.890 --> 00:54:13.800
So I don't swap.

00:54:13.800 --> 00:54:14.850
So there's no swap.

00:54:18.340 --> 00:54:19.060
What about here?

00:54:19.060 --> 00:54:20.140
Do I swap here?

00:54:23.070 --> 00:54:26.060
I open z, I saw z.

00:54:26.060 --> 00:54:29.890
z is bigger than what I
think the midpoint is,

00:54:29.890 --> 00:54:30.740
so I wouldn't swap.

00:54:30.740 --> 00:54:33.830
I only guess if
the value I reveal

00:54:33.830 --> 00:54:37.142
is less than my
guessed midpoint.

00:54:37.142 --> 00:54:40.270
If I got a value I see
bigger than my midpoint,

00:54:40.270 --> 00:54:42.256
I think I've got the big one.

00:54:42.256 --> 00:54:45.794
So there's no swap.

00:54:45.794 --> 00:54:46.460
What about here?

00:54:46.460 --> 00:54:48.490
Do I swap here?

00:54:48.490 --> 00:54:50.360
Yes, here I swap
because I open up

00:54:50.360 --> 00:54:52.714
something that's less
than my guessed midpoint,

00:54:52.714 --> 00:54:55.005
so I think I've got the small
one so I'm going to swap.

00:54:59.060 --> 00:54:59.750
What about here?

00:54:59.750 --> 00:55:01.620
Do I swap here?

00:55:01.620 --> 00:55:03.340
No swap, because I
opened up something

00:55:03.340 --> 00:55:05.070
that's bigger than midpoint.

00:55:05.070 --> 00:55:07.080
What about here?

00:55:07.080 --> 00:55:09.760
I swap.

00:55:09.760 --> 00:55:11.540
And what about here?

00:55:11.540 --> 00:55:13.532
Swap on both of them,
because both of them

00:55:13.532 --> 00:55:17.370
are smaller than my
guessed midpoint.

00:55:17.370 --> 00:55:21.210
All right, now let's figure
out if you won or you lost.

00:55:21.210 --> 00:55:26.522
So here I did not swap and I
started with a smaller value.

00:55:26.522 --> 00:55:27.230
So what happened?

00:55:27.230 --> 00:55:29.715
Did I win or lose?

00:55:29.715 --> 00:55:30.850
Lose.

00:55:30.850 --> 00:55:33.550
I opened he smaller
value and did not swap.

00:55:33.550 --> 00:55:35.970
What happened here?

00:55:35.970 --> 00:55:36.650
I win.

00:55:36.650 --> 00:55:40.020
I open the bigger
value and did not swap.

00:55:40.020 --> 00:55:42.350
Here what happened?

00:55:42.350 --> 00:55:45.950
Win, I opened the small value
when I swapped, that's a win.

00:55:45.950 --> 00:55:48.330
Here?

00:55:48.330 --> 00:55:51.280
I opened the big
value, did not swap.

00:55:51.280 --> 00:55:53.590
It's a win.

00:55:53.590 --> 00:55:57.590
Here I opened a small value
and swap, that's a win.

00:55:57.590 --> 00:56:02.812
And here I opened a big value
and swap, that's a lose.

00:56:02.812 --> 00:56:05.610
All right, now we can compute
the probability of winning.

00:56:08.240 --> 00:56:12.540
The probability of a win is
the sum of these four sample

00:56:12.540 --> 00:56:22.110
points-- y over 2n plus
z minus y over 2n plus

00:56:22.110 --> 00:56:29.220
z minus y-- whoops-- over
2n plus n minus z over 2n.

00:56:33.090 --> 00:56:38.830
That equals-- z cancels the
z, and a y cancels the y,

00:56:38.830 --> 00:56:44.820
so I've got n, one left,
n left, one z left,

00:56:44.820 --> 00:56:49.730
and one negative y left over 2n.

00:56:49.730 --> 00:56:50.990
And I can simplify that.

00:56:50.990 --> 00:56:55.420
N over 2n is 1/2, plus
now what's left over

00:56:55.420 --> 00:56:59.430
is z minus y over 2n.

00:57:02.140 --> 00:57:06.960
And we know the z and y are
different by at least 1.

00:57:06.960 --> 00:57:11.270
So this is at least
1/2 plus 1 over 2n.

00:57:14.360 --> 00:57:20.280
And so if n is 100, you've got
a 50 and 1/2% chance of winning.

00:57:20.280 --> 00:57:24.930
If n is 10, the numbers
are from 0 to 10,

00:57:24.930 --> 00:57:28.220
you've got at least
a 55% chance to win,

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:31.430
which is pretty high, OK?

00:57:33.990 --> 00:57:35.700
Any questions here?

00:57:35.700 --> 00:57:36.700
You see what's going on?

00:57:36.700 --> 00:57:39.660
So here's the zone
where you guessed right.

00:57:39.660 --> 00:57:41.190
You get the win either way.

00:57:41.190 --> 00:57:43.630
Here you guess low, and it
doesn't make any difference.

00:57:43.630 --> 00:57:44.940
You're 50-50.

00:57:44.940 --> 00:57:48.690
You guessed high and
you're 50-50 again.

00:57:48.690 --> 00:57:52.920
So guessing helps.

00:57:52.920 --> 00:57:54.500
Any questions about that?

00:57:54.500 --> 00:57:55.532
Yeah.

00:57:55.532 --> 00:57:58.484
AUDIENCE: So aren't you
assuming that-- because you say,

00:57:58.484 --> 00:58:01.436
have a range, a greater
range of numbers,

00:58:01.436 --> 00:58:04.224
that's there's a greater
chance that the number is

00:58:04.224 --> 00:58:07.840
going fall in that range.

00:58:07.840 --> 00:58:10.050
PROFESSOR: I was
the nasty guy here.

00:58:10.050 --> 00:58:12.720
I picked z and y to be
consecutive numbers, which

00:58:12.720 --> 00:58:16.575
minimized your chance of
doing well with this strategy.

00:58:16.575 --> 00:58:18.449
AUDIENCE: Because it
seems like we don't know

00:58:18.449 --> 00:58:19.574
anything about [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:22.746 --> 00:58:24.245
PROFESSOR: The
distribution of what?

00:58:24.245 --> 00:58:26.579
AUDIENCE: Of possible
other numbers

00:58:26.579 --> 00:58:27.620
in envelopes [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:27.620 --> 00:58:30.000
PROFESSOR: Right, you know
nothing about the distribution

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:32.120
because there is none.

00:58:32.120 --> 00:58:33.530
There's no randomness there.

00:58:33.530 --> 00:58:36.900
I picked worst
case numbers here.

00:58:36.900 --> 00:58:41.700
AUDIENCE: But it's still
sort of like a [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:41.700 --> 00:58:43.620
If it's 10, you still
have a better chance

00:58:43.620 --> 00:58:48.120
to swap than if you
[INAUDIBLE] below that.

00:58:48.120 --> 00:58:49.460
PROFESSOR: No.

00:58:49.460 --> 00:58:52.320
No, any deterministic
strategy you pick,

00:58:52.320 --> 00:58:54.470
if you don't guess
that random x,

00:58:54.470 --> 00:58:58.110
you will not do
better than 50-50.

00:58:58.110 --> 00:59:01.470
The only way you'd beat
50-50 is to, in your mind,

00:59:01.470 --> 00:59:07.390
make a random number 13
and 1/2 and flip if you

00:59:07.390 --> 00:59:09.780
see less than 13 and 1/2.

00:59:09.780 --> 00:59:11.640
If you come in with
a strategy that hey,

00:59:11.640 --> 00:59:15.350
10 is a small
number, out of 100,

00:59:15.350 --> 00:59:19.380
and so I'm going to
swap if I see a 10,

00:59:19.380 --> 00:59:22.600
well, no, because first it
could be-- I might have done

00:59:22.600 --> 00:59:23.720
9 or 11, either one.

00:59:23.720 --> 00:59:26.470
In fact, if I know
that's your strategy,

00:59:26.470 --> 00:59:29.530
I'm going to make a 9.

00:59:29.530 --> 00:59:32.620
And then you're
doomed in seeing a 10.

00:59:32.620 --> 00:59:34.870
AUDIENCE: So is there a
best way to pick that?

00:59:34.870 --> 00:59:38.680
PROFESSOR: Yes, I also
have an optimal strategy.

00:59:38.680 --> 00:59:41.350
In fact, there's two
interesting things

00:59:41.350 --> 00:59:43.630
about this game
which we won't prove.

00:59:43.630 --> 00:59:46.500
The first thing we'll prove,
we will prove but it's true,

00:59:46.500 --> 00:59:50.470
is this is the optimal
strategy for you.

00:59:50.470 --> 00:59:53.520
And my optimal
strategy is to pick

00:59:53.520 --> 00:59:57.820
a random value of y
between 0 and n minus 1,

00:59:57.820 --> 01:00:01.217
and then to make z be one more.

01:00:01.217 --> 01:00:03.050
And the way to think
about this, and there's

01:00:03.050 --> 01:00:06.520
whole classes you can
take on game theory,

01:00:06.520 --> 01:00:11.170
is that suppose I do
pick my guys randomly

01:00:11.170 --> 01:00:14.900
by picking a random y
uniformly from 0 to n minus 1.

01:00:14.900 --> 01:00:18.510
So my smaller number is
anything between 0 and 99,

01:00:18.510 --> 01:00:22.550
equally likely, and then the
bigger number's just one more.

01:00:22.550 --> 01:00:24.340
So if I picked 92
for the random one,

01:00:24.340 --> 01:00:26.360
the next one's going to be 93.

01:00:26.360 --> 01:00:30.350
If that's my strategy,
even if I tell you that,

01:00:30.350 --> 01:00:35.354
you cannot do any better than
getting 1/2 plus 1 over 2n

01:00:35.354 --> 01:00:37.770
probability of winning, no
matter what you do in the whole

01:00:37.770 --> 01:00:40.420
world, OK?

01:00:40.420 --> 01:00:43.620
And if you use
this strategy here,

01:00:43.620 --> 01:00:47.950
no matter what I do, even
knowing that's your strategy,

01:00:47.950 --> 01:00:52.730
I can't keep you from
getting this much.

01:00:52.730 --> 01:00:55.620
It's called a minimax solution.

01:00:55.620 --> 01:00:59.170
So my optimal strategy is to
pick uniformly in 0 to 99,

01:00:59.170 --> 01:01:00.470
and the next one's one more.

01:01:00.470 --> 01:01:02.880
Your optimal strategy is this.

01:01:02.880 --> 01:01:06.447
Pick a number uniformly in
the half integers there,

01:01:06.447 --> 01:01:08.030
and swap if you see
something smaller.

01:01:08.030 --> 01:01:10.310
And there's no better strategy.

01:01:10.310 --> 01:01:12.270
In fact, any
deterministic strategy,

01:01:12.270 --> 01:01:14.220
you don't do better than 50-50.

01:01:14.220 --> 01:01:20.640
The optimal strategies require
randomness for each of us.

01:01:20.640 --> 01:01:27.320
OK, any more questions about
what happened here, this game?

01:01:27.320 --> 01:01:28.642
Yeah.

01:01:28.642 --> 01:01:30.205
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
when you see

01:01:30.205 --> 01:01:32.971
a small number you're going
to swap, does that just mean

01:01:32.971 --> 01:01:35.380
[INAUDIBLE]?

01:01:35.380 --> 01:01:39.220
PROFESSOR: Yeah, basically,
yeah, that's what it means.

01:01:39.220 --> 01:01:41.650
Effectively, that 50
is your random number.

01:01:41.650 --> 01:01:44.180
If you think OK, if I see less
than 50, I'm going to swap,

01:01:44.180 --> 01:01:45.240
bigger than 50 I don't.

01:01:45.240 --> 01:01:46.710
Now you have to
decide what happens

01:01:46.710 --> 01:01:49.010
at 50, if you saw exactly 50.

01:01:49.010 --> 01:01:52.819
So you'd probably go in at
49 and 1/2 and 50 and 1/2.

01:01:52.819 --> 01:01:54.610
And so that could be
construed as that way.

01:01:54.610 --> 01:01:57.400
But you didn't pick it
randomly, and that sort

01:01:57.400 --> 01:02:00.130
of human intuition,
to swap so I could

01:02:00.130 --> 01:02:02.980
use that now to
design my strategy,

01:02:02.980 --> 01:02:07.780
knowing that your random
numbers could be 50 and 1/2, OK?

01:02:10.500 --> 01:02:12.010
No, I'll be 50-50
because what I'll

01:02:12.010 --> 01:02:13.740
do, if I know that's
your strategy,

01:02:13.740 --> 01:02:14.990
my numbers will be 1 and 2.

01:02:17.760 --> 01:02:19.480
Well, when you do
these analyses,

01:02:19.480 --> 01:02:23.540
you sort of, if it's declared
that's it, I can assume that.

01:02:23.540 --> 01:02:25.486
And I might actually guess that.

01:02:25.486 --> 01:02:28.150
In fact, that's why I did pick
two very small numbers and two

01:02:28.150 --> 01:02:29.590
very big numbers.

01:02:29.590 --> 01:02:31.170
But given the
perverse nature here,

01:02:31.170 --> 01:02:33.830
when you saw the big
number, you got rid of it,

01:02:33.830 --> 01:02:37.780
and when you saw the
small number, you kept it.

01:02:37.780 --> 01:02:39.820
So you sort of did
reverse psychology

01:02:39.820 --> 01:02:43.900
and it worked out, by chance,
that it worked out that.

01:02:43.900 --> 01:02:47.047
Normally it would go
the other way, I think.

01:02:47.047 --> 01:02:48.880
Of course, you've all
seen enough games now,

01:02:48.880 --> 01:02:53.800
you know to do the
non-standard thing, I think.

01:02:53.800 --> 01:02:56.409
Now, this kind of thinking
comes up all the time

01:02:56.409 --> 01:02:57.700
in computer science algorithms.

01:02:57.700 --> 01:02:59.550
You know, the
protocol that's used

01:02:59.550 --> 01:03:02.720
to communicate across
a network, ethernet,

01:03:02.720 --> 01:03:05.750
shared bus is randomized.

01:03:05.750 --> 01:03:09.060
Each entity that wants to use
the bus flips a random number,

01:03:09.060 --> 01:03:10.040
flips a random coin.

01:03:10.040 --> 01:03:11.430
You could think of it that way.

01:03:11.430 --> 01:03:14.270
And it broadcasts
with that probability.

01:03:14.270 --> 01:03:16.150
And if there's a
collision, it backs off

01:03:16.150 --> 01:03:18.530
and chooses a smaller
probability next time.

01:03:18.530 --> 01:03:21.400
And if it gets through, then it
tries to cram a bunch of stuff

01:03:21.400 --> 01:03:24.060
through, until you
get a collision again.

01:03:24.060 --> 01:03:26.680
The best algorithms for
sorting a list of numbers

01:03:26.680 --> 01:03:29.780
are randomized, quick sort,
which you'll see in 6046,

01:03:29.780 --> 01:03:31.800
is a randomized algorithm.

01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:33.170
In fact, it's not dissimilar.

01:03:33.170 --> 01:03:37.017
You guess a random value
and split all the numbers

01:03:37.017 --> 01:03:38.100
based on the random value.

01:03:38.100 --> 01:03:41.030
Who's bigger, who's smaller,
and then you [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:41.030 --> 01:03:44.670
You do things like that.

01:03:44.670 --> 01:03:49.900
OK, that's all I'm going to say
about uniform distributions.

01:03:49.900 --> 01:03:54.400
Next I want to talk about
the binomial distribution.

01:03:54.400 --> 01:03:59.300
And this is the most
important distribution

01:03:59.300 --> 01:04:02.510
in computer science, and
probably the most important

01:04:02.510 --> 01:04:07.730
in all of discrete
calculations in the sciences.

01:04:07.730 --> 01:04:10.480
In continuous distributions,
you get the normal distribution.

01:04:10.480 --> 01:04:16.562
But, for discrete problems, the
binomial is the most important.

01:04:16.562 --> 01:04:17.910
And there's two versions.

01:04:17.910 --> 01:04:21.820
There's the unbiased
binomial distribution

01:04:21.820 --> 01:04:23.301
and then there's the biased one.

01:04:28.462 --> 01:04:30.170
Now this one's a little
more complicated.

01:04:30.170 --> 01:04:34.460
You've got a parameter n again,
and the distribution function

01:04:34.460 --> 01:04:37.130
on k, probability
of getting k is

01:04:37.130 --> 01:04:42.000
n choose k times
2 to the minus n.

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:48.560
And n is at least 1, and
k is between 0 and n.

01:04:48.560 --> 01:05:01.790
And then for the general
binomial distribution,

01:05:01.790 --> 01:05:04.140
we have fn of k, the
probability of getting

01:05:04.140 --> 01:05:10.270
k is n choose k times--
actually, it's fnp,

01:05:10.270 --> 01:05:12.500
there's another
parameter p here.

01:05:12.500 --> 01:05:17.585
p to the k times 1 minus
p to the n minus k power.

01:05:17.585 --> 01:05:20.640
And p is a value between
0 to 1 typically.

01:05:20.640 --> 01:05:23.330
It's a probability of
something happening.

01:05:23.330 --> 01:05:26.560
So in the general
case, you've got nnp.

01:05:26.560 --> 01:05:30.750
The unbiased case
corresponds to when p is 1/2.

01:05:30.750 --> 01:05:35.200
Because if p is 1/2, you get 2
to the minus k and 2 the minus

01:05:35.200 --> 01:05:38.600
n minus k, and that's
just 2 to the minus n.

01:05:38.600 --> 01:05:40.990
So you can think of this
as the case when p is 1/2.

01:05:46.330 --> 01:05:50.100
All right, to give
you an example why

01:05:50.100 --> 01:05:54.230
this is so important, why
it comes up all the time.

01:05:54.230 --> 01:05:59.030
Imagine that you've got a
system with n components.

01:05:59.030 --> 01:06:03.159
And that each component
fails with probability p.

01:06:03.159 --> 01:06:05.590
And you want to know the
probability of having

01:06:05.590 --> 01:06:07.565
some number of failures.

01:06:15.160 --> 01:06:22.890
So for example,
there's n components

01:06:22.890 --> 01:06:32.900
and each fails independently--
in fact, mutually

01:06:32.900 --> 01:06:40.190
independently--
with probability p.

01:06:42.790 --> 01:06:44.620
And p will be between 0 and 1.

01:06:47.450 --> 01:06:51.400
And now we're interested
in the number of failures,

01:06:51.400 --> 01:06:54.250
so we'll make R be a
random variable that

01:06:54.250 --> 01:06:57.245
tells us the number
of failed components.

01:07:02.810 --> 01:07:05.750
And it turns out
the answer is simply

01:07:05.750 --> 01:07:09.420
that function, which
we'll prove is a theorem.

01:07:09.420 --> 01:07:19.005
The probability that R equals k
is simply fnp of k [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:23.870 --> 01:07:26.310
So the general
binomial distribution

01:07:26.310 --> 01:07:29.850
gives you the distribution
on the number of failures

01:07:29.850 --> 01:07:32.060
in a system with
n components where

01:07:32.060 --> 01:07:34.638
they fail with probability p.

01:07:34.638 --> 01:07:36.120
So let's prove that.

01:07:47.990 --> 01:07:51.920
To do that, we're going to
construct our tree again.

01:07:51.920 --> 01:07:55.000
It's a little big because
you've got n components.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:57.180
But you look at the
first component,

01:07:57.180 --> 01:08:00.480
and that can fail or not.

01:08:00.480 --> 01:08:02.430
And it fails a probability p.

01:08:02.430 --> 01:08:05.710
It's OK with
probability 1 minus p.

01:08:05.710 --> 01:08:08.132
And you have the
second component.

01:08:08.132 --> 01:08:10.740
It can fail or not.

01:08:10.740 --> 01:08:12.390
Again p and 1 minus p.

01:08:20.210 --> 01:08:22.733
And you keep on going until
you get to the nth component.

01:08:27.229 --> 01:08:32.850
And that can fail or not, the
probability p or 1 minus p,

01:08:32.850 --> 01:08:33.950
in general down here.

01:08:40.140 --> 01:08:42.960
And now we look at all the
sample points out here.

01:08:47.120 --> 01:08:54.160
And it's all length and
vectors of failure or not.

01:08:54.160 --> 01:08:58.979
So the top sample point here
would be n good components.

01:09:01.750 --> 01:09:05.370
All right, the next one would
be the first n minus 1 are good,

01:09:05.370 --> 01:09:08.420
the last one failed.

01:09:08.420 --> 01:09:10.170
All the way down
to the very bottom,

01:09:10.170 --> 01:09:11.380
you can have all n fail.

01:09:14.871 --> 01:09:17.370
All right, so how many sample
points are there in the sample

01:09:17.370 --> 01:09:23.170
space with n components?

01:09:23.170 --> 01:09:24.830
2 to the n, all right?

01:09:24.830 --> 01:09:26.760
Because you've got n positions.

01:09:26.760 --> 01:09:28.960
There's two choices
for each value there.

01:09:32.160 --> 01:09:35.010
Now how many of
the sample points

01:09:35.010 --> 01:09:40.109
have exactly k
failed components?

01:09:40.109 --> 01:09:43.210
Out of the 2 to the
n, how many correspond

01:09:43.210 --> 01:09:44.819
to k of the components fail?

01:09:48.779 --> 01:09:51.820
n choose k-- now this
goes back to counting.

01:09:51.820 --> 01:09:55.690
Remember the
binomial coefficient.

01:09:55.690 --> 01:10:06.960
So there are n choose
k sample points have

01:10:06.960 --> 01:10:08.400
k failed components.

01:10:16.350 --> 01:10:18.770
All right, what's the
probability of a sample

01:10:18.770 --> 01:10:21.560
point with k failed components?

01:10:24.184 --> 01:10:30.950
Well, I took k branches
with a failure.

01:10:30.950 --> 01:10:36.480
Each of those gives
me a p, p to the k.

01:10:36.480 --> 01:10:40.900
And I took n minus k
branches with no failure.

01:10:40.900 --> 01:10:43.340
Each one of those
multiplies by a 1 minus p.

01:10:46.370 --> 01:10:50.080
So no matter how I
got my k failures,

01:10:50.080 --> 01:10:54.000
the probability for a particular
sample point with k failures

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:58.170
is just that, because I had
p get factored in k times,

01:10:58.170 --> 01:11:00.900
in the failures, 1
minus p get factored

01:11:00.900 --> 01:11:03.381
in n minus k times
for the situations

01:11:03.381 --> 01:11:04.630
where it worked out all right.

01:11:07.970 --> 01:11:10.980
So I've got this
many sample points.

01:11:10.980 --> 01:11:22.870
Each of them has probability
p to the k times 1

01:11:22.870 --> 01:11:25.300
minus p n minus k.

01:11:28.230 --> 01:11:30.420
Any questions about that,
why that's the case?

01:11:33.692 --> 01:11:35.650
All right, so now I can
compute the probability

01:11:35.650 --> 01:11:38.730
there are k failures.

01:11:38.730 --> 01:11:43.040
The probability that
R equals k is simply n

01:11:43.040 --> 01:11:47.870
choose k, number of sample
points times their probability,

01:11:47.870 --> 01:11:51.920
since they're all the
same for k failures.

01:11:51.920 --> 01:11:55.830
And that, of course,
is just the formula

01:11:55.830 --> 01:11:59.290
for the general
binomial distribution.

01:11:59.290 --> 01:12:06.146
So that equals fnp of k, which
is what we are trying to prove.

01:12:11.570 --> 01:12:14.050
OK.

01:12:14.050 --> 01:12:16.840
Any questions about that?

01:12:16.840 --> 01:12:18.980
So that's why it's
important, because there's

01:12:18.980 --> 01:12:22.100
a lot of situations where
you're interested in the number

01:12:22.100 --> 01:12:24.330
of-- if you had n
possible things,

01:12:24.330 --> 01:12:26.590
what's the chance
k of them happen?

01:12:26.590 --> 01:12:30.630
And it's just given
by this formula.

01:12:30.630 --> 01:12:36.850
Now you can calculate this,
but, if I just told you,

01:12:36.850 --> 01:12:45.310
for example, maybe I'm looking
at n is 100 and even p is 1/2,

01:12:45.310 --> 01:12:47.490
you know, what's the
probability that we'd

01:12:47.490 --> 01:12:51.690
get 25-- say, what's
the probably if getting

01:12:51.690 --> 01:12:54.140
50 failed components?

01:12:54.140 --> 01:12:58.480
Or if I flip 100 coins
and they're fair.

01:12:58.480 --> 01:13:00.730
So probability half
of getting a heads.

01:13:00.730 --> 01:13:05.680
What's the chance I actually
get 50 heads in 100 coins?

01:13:05.680 --> 01:13:10.950
Looking at that, it's not
so clear what the answer is.

01:13:10.950 --> 01:13:14.570
In fact, let's test
intuition here, for this.

01:13:14.570 --> 01:13:16.140
We're going to
take a little vote

01:13:16.140 --> 01:13:19.720
to see how good you are
looking at that formula,

01:13:19.720 --> 01:13:23.420
or what your intuition is about
the probability of getting

01:13:23.420 --> 01:13:24.695
exactly 50 heads.

01:13:29.240 --> 01:13:34.534
It could be between 1 and
1/2, a half and a tenth,

01:13:34.534 --> 01:13:40.030
a tenth and a hundredth, a
hundredth and one thousandth,

01:13:40.030 --> 01:13:44.259
a thousandth and a
millionth, and 0.

01:13:44.259 --> 01:13:46.050
I want to know what's
the probability, when

01:13:46.050 --> 01:13:48.810
you flip 100 mutually
independent coins,

01:13:48.810 --> 01:13:52.370
you get exactly 50 heads?

01:13:52.370 --> 01:13:54.870
How many people think
it's at least a half,

01:13:54.870 --> 01:13:57.900
that you get half heads?

01:13:57.900 --> 01:13:58.920
Nobody likes that.

01:13:58.920 --> 01:14:02.640
How many people think it's
between a half and a tenth?

01:14:02.640 --> 01:14:03.890
One vote.

01:14:03.890 --> 01:14:06.280
A tenth and a hundredth?

01:14:06.280 --> 01:14:06.780
More.

01:14:08.939 --> 01:14:10.730
Doesn't it have to be
at least a hundredth?

01:14:10.730 --> 01:14:12.354
That's sort of the
most likely outcome.

01:14:12.354 --> 01:14:16.600
There's only-- how many think
a hundredth and a thousandth?

01:14:16.600 --> 01:14:17.350
All right.

01:14:17.350 --> 01:14:19.840
A thousandth and a millionth?

01:14:19.840 --> 01:14:22.040
Whoa, so you've got
to believe it is not

01:14:22.040 --> 01:14:25.560
likely to get exactly 50
heads when I flip 100 coins.

01:14:25.560 --> 01:14:28.690
All right, well the
answer is actually

01:14:28.690 --> 01:14:30.660
between a tenth and
a hundredth here.

01:14:33.730 --> 01:14:34.910
It's about 8%.

01:14:34.910 --> 01:14:36.570
And we're going to compute that.

01:14:36.570 --> 01:14:38.330
But here's another one.

01:14:38.330 --> 01:14:40.370
I flip 100 coins.

01:14:40.370 --> 01:14:46.520
What's the probability of
getting at most 25 heads?

01:14:46.520 --> 01:14:48.605
So here, doesn't have
to be exactly 25.

01:14:48.605 --> 01:14:53.400
It could be 25, 24, 23, 22,
all the way down to no heads.

01:14:53.400 --> 01:14:55.560
So a lot of chances, all right?

01:14:55.560 --> 01:14:57.630
To get at most 25 heads.

01:14:57.630 --> 01:15:00.200
How many people think it's here?

01:15:00.200 --> 01:15:02.770
Some, yeah, you've
got a lot of chances.

01:15:02.770 --> 01:15:04.885
How about here?

01:15:04.885 --> 01:15:06.230
Yeah, OK.

01:15:06.230 --> 01:15:09.858
What about between a
tenth and a hundredth?

01:15:09.858 --> 01:15:12.940
One person, two people left.

01:15:12.940 --> 01:15:15.930
Between a hundredth
and a thousandth?

01:15:15.930 --> 01:15:16.620
Nobody left?

01:15:16.620 --> 01:15:18.050
Anybody here?

01:15:18.050 --> 01:15:20.630
Thousandth and a millionth?

01:15:20.630 --> 01:15:22.340
One person is left,
less than a million.

01:15:22.340 --> 01:15:24.630
1 in a million?

01:15:24.630 --> 01:15:25.880
There's the contrarian.

01:15:25.880 --> 01:15:31.310
And you're right, the chance
of getting 25 or less heads

01:15:31.310 --> 01:15:34.330
is less than 1 in a million.

01:15:34.330 --> 01:15:39.020
So if somebody does it, his
name better be Persi Diaconis.

01:15:39.020 --> 01:15:42.710
To get it consistently to 70,
[INAUDIBLE] 25 or fewer heads.

01:15:42.710 --> 01:15:48.160
You get 75 tails or more is
extremely unlikely, all right?

01:15:48.160 --> 01:15:50.660
So to see why that's
the case, we've

01:15:50.660 --> 01:15:53.900
got to do a little
work on this formula.

01:15:53.900 --> 01:15:57.820
Because we're saying that if
we sum this up for k ending 100

01:15:57.820 --> 01:16:01.470
and k being 0 to 25,
and p being a half,

01:16:01.470 --> 01:16:04.600
it's an incredibly tiny number.

01:16:04.600 --> 01:16:05.922
So let's see why that is.

01:16:05.922 --> 01:16:07.380
And this phenomenon
is course going

01:16:07.380 --> 01:16:09.690
to be important in
computer science

01:16:09.690 --> 01:16:12.290
because it's going to enable
you to tell almost exactly how

01:16:12.290 --> 01:16:15.120
many components are going
to fail in a system,

01:16:15.120 --> 01:16:16.617
if they're mutually independent.

01:16:30.624 --> 01:16:33.040
All right, now I'm not going
to drag you through the math.

01:16:33.040 --> 01:16:36.760
It's bad enough I'm going
to write it on the board.

01:16:36.760 --> 01:16:40.320
There's a bunch of
this in the text.

01:16:40.320 --> 01:16:43.560
And instead of k, I'm going to
represent by a parameter alpha

01:16:43.560 --> 01:16:46.452
times n to be the integer k.

01:16:46.452 --> 01:16:50.330
All right, this will replace
k with a new parameter alpha.

01:16:50.330 --> 01:16:54.190
It's at most, and also it's
asymptotically equivalent

01:16:54.190 --> 01:16:58.390
using tilde-- both of those are
true-- to this nasty looking

01:16:58.390 --> 01:17:08.900
expression, 2 to the
alpha log p over alpha

01:17:08.900 --> 01:17:18.740
plus 1 minus alpha log 1 minus
p over 1 minus alpha times

01:17:18.740 --> 01:17:26.000
and n-- that's a big number,
it's 100-- over square root 2

01:17:26.000 --> 01:17:31.840
pi alpha 1 minus alpha n.

01:17:31.840 --> 01:17:33.875
And this, of course,
alpha is between 0 and 1.

01:17:37.790 --> 01:17:39.970
Now when you do the
derivative on this thing,

01:17:39.970 --> 01:17:42.840
it turns out its maximum
value is when alpha equals p.

01:17:51.320 --> 01:17:57.580
And when you have alpha equals
p, you get log of 1 is 0,

01:17:57.580 --> 01:17:58.640
log of 1 is 0.

01:17:58.640 --> 01:18:03.090
All this messy stuff goes
away and we just get that.

01:18:03.090 --> 01:18:10.520
And so in that case, fnp
of pn is at most, and also

01:18:10.520 --> 01:18:19.130
asymptotically equal to 1 over
square root 2 pi p 1 minus p n.

01:18:21.650 --> 01:18:23.860
And now you can plug in
values and compute things.

01:18:23.860 --> 01:18:26.880
For example, if
I flip 100 coins,

01:18:26.880 --> 01:18:29.720
and I want to know the
probability of getting 50--

01:18:29.720 --> 01:18:32.240
that means alpha's a
half, and they're fair,

01:18:32.240 --> 01:18:38.080
which means p is a
half, the answer is 8%.

01:18:38.080 --> 01:18:42.240
So n equals 100 coins,
p is a half, then

01:18:42.240 --> 01:18:44.730
the probability of 50 heads.

01:18:49.370 --> 01:18:55.840
I just plug in p is a half here,
I get 1 over square root 50 pi,

01:18:55.840 --> 01:19:00.670
which equals 0.080 and so forth.

01:19:00.670 --> 01:19:05.905
So there's an 8% chance of
getting exactly 50 heads.

01:19:05.905 --> 01:19:07.280
Now let's look at
the probability

01:19:07.280 --> 01:19:10.670
of getting 25 or fewer.

01:19:10.670 --> 01:19:13.548
And we'll see why that
is so surprisingly small.

01:19:30.170 --> 01:19:38.160
OK, so for n equal
100 and p equal

01:19:38.160 --> 01:19:42.630
a half an alpha equal a quarter,
because we want 25 heads,

01:19:42.630 --> 01:19:46.110
I'll get exactly 25 heads first.

01:19:46.110 --> 01:19:52.460
Probability of 25
heads is at most,

01:19:52.460 --> 01:19:57.900
well that square root thing
comes out to about 0.09.

01:19:57.900 --> 01:20:00.230
Then I get 2 to something.

01:20:00.230 --> 01:20:09.380
I get 2 to the minus, all those
logs come out the 0.1887 times

01:20:09.380 --> 01:20:12.920
n, which is the
kicker, that's 100.

01:20:12.920 --> 01:20:16.730
So I get a 2 to the
minus 18th here.

01:20:16.730 --> 01:20:21.080
And that makes this
thing be smaller than

01:20:21.080 --> 01:20:26.230
or equal about to 1.913
times 10 to the minus 7.

01:20:26.230 --> 01:20:29.960
So about 1 in 5 million.

01:20:29.960 --> 01:20:32.760
The reason this gets
so small is because you

01:20:32.760 --> 01:20:35.872
get the n in that
exponent up there.

01:20:35.872 --> 01:20:37.330
And of course, this
is all computed

01:20:37.330 --> 01:20:39.560
using Stirling's formula,
if you actually want

01:20:39.560 --> 01:20:41.370
to go through the calculations.

01:20:41.370 --> 01:20:46.190
You go start with n choose
k, which is your n factorial,

01:20:46.190 --> 01:20:48.980
times over k factorial
n minus k factorial.

01:20:48.980 --> 01:20:52.280
Plug in Stirling's formula and
you do a bunch of messy stuff,

01:20:52.280 --> 01:20:54.840
and these things pop out.

01:20:54.840 --> 01:20:57.720
And so it gets exponentially
small, exponentially fast.

01:20:57.720 --> 01:21:00.270
In fact, if you were
to plot this thing,

01:21:00.270 --> 01:21:03.510
if you plot the binomial
distribution function,

01:21:03.510 --> 01:21:06.520
it looks something like this.

01:21:17.330 --> 01:21:21.380
All right, so I have
0 to n, and then I

01:21:21.380 --> 01:21:24.957
have pn, which is the maximum.

01:21:24.957 --> 01:21:25.915
Here's the probability.

01:21:25.915 --> 01:21:28.560
It goes 0 to 1.

01:21:28.560 --> 01:21:33.310
And your maximum value is here
at 8% in the case of 100 coins,

01:21:33.310 --> 01:21:39.980
and it just zooms down
exponential small.

01:21:39.980 --> 01:21:43.110
You can't even draw because
it gets so small so fast.

01:21:43.110 --> 01:21:50.840
This height here is
about 1 over root n.

01:21:50.840 --> 01:21:55.920
And this width here of
the hump, is about root n.

01:21:55.920 --> 01:22:01.470
And these things zoom down
to 0, exponentially fast.

01:22:01.470 --> 01:22:04.220
And so that's what the binomial
distribution looks like.

01:22:04.220 --> 01:22:12.110
And so it says that you are very
likely to be very close to pn

01:22:12.110 --> 01:22:15.494
heads, or pn things happening.

01:22:15.494 --> 01:22:17.660
And I won't go through the
math now-- probably do it

01:22:17.660 --> 01:22:20.300
in recitation
tomorrow-- of computing

01:22:20.300 --> 01:22:23.770
at most 25 heads, which is
the cumulative distribution

01:22:23.770 --> 01:22:25.222
function.

01:22:25.222 --> 01:22:26.930
And this comes up in
all sorts of places.

01:22:26.930 --> 01:22:29.920
Like you have a noisy
communications channel,

01:22:29.920 --> 01:22:33.620
and every bit as
dropped with 1% chance.

01:22:33.620 --> 01:22:35.340
If you have 10,000
bits, you'd like

01:22:35.340 --> 01:22:40.000
to know, what's the
probability I lost 2% of them

01:22:40.000 --> 01:22:42.990
when I have 1% failure rate?

01:22:42.990 --> 01:22:46.050
The chance of losing
2% out of 10,000

01:22:46.050 --> 01:22:49.500
is like 2 to the minus 60 if
they're mutually independent.

01:22:49.500 --> 01:22:52.001
So no chance of losing 2%.

01:22:52.001 --> 01:22:52.876
All right, very good.

01:22:52.876 --> 01:22:55.730
We'll do more this in
recitation tomorrow.

